<HEADLINE>
<P>
L.A. TEACHER SALARY DISPUTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In response to Frank del Olmo's column "Who Gains if UTLA Alienates the 
Parents?" (Op-Ed Page, Feb. 15), I say, what a shallow analysis, premised on a 
false assumption! 
</P>
<P>
The current labor dispute between United Teachers-Los Angeles and the Los 
Angeles Unified School District isn't interfering with the education inner-city 
parents want their children to get. Education is proceeding as if the teachers 
had a contract. 
</P>
<P>
So far only the families of teachers observing the boycott of certain 
"non-academic" duties have suffered financially, because of docked paychecks. 
</P>
<P>
I can't see how teachers can be painted as selfish and shortsighted when we put 
our livelihood on the line every year to reach a fair settlement -- not just 
for ourselves, but also for the students. 
</P>
<P>
The public should keep in mind that poor working conditions for teachers mean 
poor learning conditions for students, and that low pay equals low morale and 
mediocre performance. 
</P>
<P>
The battle for good education is led by the teachers. We pay the price every 
year through stressful and bitter negotiations, only to have oversimplistic 
analyses like Del Olmo's paint us as cynics. 
</P>
<P>
When teachers across this country are paid their comparable worth, boycotting, 
slow-downs and strikes will be a thing of the past. 
</P>
<P>
If we treasure our kids, we should pay teachers commensurate to the social 
value they represent. Short of that, I'll stand by the union. 
</P>
<P>
STERLING DELONE 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
