<P>
INDIA CUTS DEFENSE OUTLAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
India's government has slashed defense spending and diverted funds to fight 
hunger and illiteracy and provide housing for the homeless. The unprecedented 
reduction in defense spending was contained in the government's budget for 
1989-90, introduced in Parliament by Finance Minister S. B. Chavan. India will 
spend $133 million less on defense in the 1989-90 fiscal year compared to the 
previous year, Chavan said. He pledged to spend $1.1 billion on aid for hunger, 
illiteracy and the homeless, an increase of $333 million from last year. The 
added funds for social programs will be raised directly from taxing the 
upper-middle classes, including an 8% surcharge on annual incomes of more than 
$3,300. 
</P>
