</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An Oklahoma horseman filed a $4.6 million federal lawsuit Wednesday claiming 
fraud in the 1987 All American Futurity because the winning horse in the 
$2-million New Mexico race was drugged. 
</P>
<P>
The New Mexico Racing Commission ruled in January 1988 that Elans Special, the 
first filly to win the race in 10 years, was drugged twice before the All 
American Futurity, considered the Kentucky Derby of quarter horse racing. 
</P>
<P>
Doyle Rice, owner of second-place finisher Elaina Rae, asks in the suit filed 
in U.S. District Court in Tulsa, Okla. that Elans Special be disqualified as 
the winner and his horse receive the title. 
