<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
EC OKS STRONG OZONE LAYER PACT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BRUSSELS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
European Community environment ministers agreed today on a surprise pact that 
would virtually eliminate household gases used in refrigerators and spray cans 
that are destroying the Earth's protective ozone layer. 
</P>
<P>
An EC spokesman said the ministers had agreed to eliminate chlorofluorocarbon 
production and consumption by the year 2000, and to an 85% cut as soon as 
possible. 
</P>
<P>
"This is a quantum leap forward," Britain's Lord Caithness told reporters. The 
ministers had originally expected to agree only on an 85% cut by the end of the 
century. 
</P>
<P>
About 40 countries agreed in a treaty signed in Montreal in 1987 to halve CFC 
production by 1998. Diplomats said the 12-nation community wants to take the 
lead in pushing the world toward total cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
